Let the radius of $\odot P$ be $r_{1}$, and the radius of $\odot Q$ be $r_{2}$. Then, according to the power of a point theorem, we have $O P \leq \sqrt{1-\mathrm{PZ}_{1} \cdot \mathrm{PZ}_{2}} \leq \sqrt{1-\mathrm{r}_{1}{ }^{2}}$, $\mathrm{PQ} \leq \sqrt{\mathrm{r}^{2}-\mathrm{QZ} \cdot Q Z_{4}} \leq \sqrt{\mathrm{r}_{1}^{2}-\mathrm{r}_{2}^{2}}$, and $Q \mathrm{Z}_{5} \leq \mathrm{r}_{2}$. Therefore, we know
$$
\begin{array}{l}
\left|z_{5}\right| \leq O P+P Q+Q Z_{5} \leq \sqrt{1-r_{1}{ }^{2}}+\sqrt{r_{1}{ }^{2}-r_{2}{ }^{2}}+r_{2} \\
\leq \sqrt{3\left[\left(1-r_{1}{ }^{2}\right)+\left(r_{1}{ }^{2}-r^{2}{ }^{2}\right)+r_{2}{ }^{2}\right]}=\sqrt{3}
\end{array}
$$

On the other hand, if we take $z_{1}=\frac{\sqrt{2}+1}{\sqrt{3}} ; z_{2}=\frac{-\sqrt{2}+i}{\sqrt{3}} ; z_{3}=\frac{1+2 i}{\sqrt{3}} ; z_{4}=\frac{-1+2 i}{\sqrt{3}} ; z_{5}=\sqrt{3} \mathrm{i}$, then the conditions are satisfied.

