soln_description:
Sure, here is the translated text:

```
II. Proof: Let $f(x)=\frac{x}{n}+\frac{n}{x}\left(x \in \mathbf{R}^{+}\right)$, and let $0 < x_1 < x_2$.
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Then } f\left(x_1\right)-f\left(x_2\right)=\left(\frac{x_1}{n}+\frac{n}{x_1}\right)-\left(\frac{x_2}{n}+\frac{n}{x_2}\right) \\
=\frac{x_1-x_2}{n}+\frac{n\left(x_2-x_1\right)}{x_1 x_2} \\
=\frac{\left(x_1-x_2\right)\left(x_1 x_2-n^2\right)}{n x_1 x_2} .
\end{array}
Since $0 < x_1 < x_2$, we have $x_1 - x_2 < 0$ and $x_1 x_2 > 0$.
\begin{array}{l}
\text{If } x_1 x_2 \geqslant n^2, \text{ then } f\left(x_1\right)-f\left(x_2\right) \leqslant 0, \text{ so } f\left(x_1\right) \leqslant f\left(x_2\right). \\
\text{If } x_1 x_2 < n^2, \text{ then } f\left(x_1\right)-f\left(x_2\right) > 0, \text{ so } f\left(x_1\right) > f\left(x_2\right).
\end{array}
Thus, $f(x)$ is decreasing on $\left(0, \sqrt{n^2}\right)$ and increasing on $\left(\sqrt{n^2}, +\infty\right)$.
\begin{array}{l}
\text{To find the minimum value of } f(x), \text{ we set } x = \sqrt{n^2} = n. \\
\text{Then } f(n) = \frac{n}{n} + \frac{n}{n} = 2.
\end{array}
We need to show that $f(x) \geqslant 2$ for all $x \in \mathbf{R}^{+}$.
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Consider } f(x) - 2 = \frac{x}{n} + \frac{n}{x} - 2. \\
\text{We need to show that } \frac{x}{n} + \frac{n}{x} - 2 \geqslant 0.
\end{array}
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Let } g(x) = \frac{x}{n} + \frac{n}{x} - 2. \\
\text{Then } g'(x) = \frac{1}{n} - \frac{n}{x^2}.
\end{array}
Setting $g'(x) = 0$, we get:
\begin{array}{l}
\frac{1}{n} - \frac{n}{x^2} = 0 \\
\frac{1}{n} = \frac{n}{x^2} \\
x^2 = n^2 \\
x = n.
\end{array}
\begin{array}{l}
\text{At } x = n, \text{ we have } g(n) = \frac{n}{n} + \frac{n}{n} - 2 = 2 - 2 = 0.
\end{array}
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Since } g(x) \text{ is minimized at } x = n, \text{ we have } g(x) \geqslant 0 \text{ for all } x \in \mathbf{R}^{+}.
\end{array}
Thus, $f(x) \geqslant 2$ for all $x \in \mathbf{R}^{+}$.
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Now, consider } f(x) = \frac{x}{n} + \frac{n}{x} \text{ for } n \geqslant 4. \\
\text{We need to show that } f(x) \geqslant 2 \text{ for all } x \in \mathbf{R}^{+}.
\end{array}
\begin{array}{l}
\text{Since } f(x) \text{ is minimized at } x = n, \text{ we have } f(n) = 2.
\end{array}
\begin{array}{l}
\text{For } n \geqslant 4, \text{ we have } f(x) \geqslant 2.
\end{array}
Hence, the inequality holds for $n \geqslant 4$.
Therefore, (3) holds, i.e., the original proposition holds.
```

